;; 08-complexity-and-limits.slat
;; Book of CS Curriculum — 08-complexity-and-limits

(chapter
  :book             "Book of CS Curriculum"
  :chapter-number   8
  :title            "08-complexity-and-limits"
  :source-path      "/Users/alfred/code/curator/BOOK/A-branch-scheme-books/cs-curriculum/08-complexity-and-limits.slat"
  :size             7618
  :sha256           "7721e55079eba2e6"
  :prose
"(chapter
  :n 15
  :title \"Complexity — how big is 'big'\"
  :book \"book-of-cs-curriculum\"

  :scene
  \"You are asked to guess how long a task will take. Ten items? A
   moment. A hundred items? Also fast. A million items? Depends
   entirely on which task. Some tasks are 'a million times slower'
   for a million items. Some are 'twenty times slower.' Some are
   'take-more-time-than-the-universe-has' slower. Big-O notation is
   the small vocabulary for talking about which shape a task is.\"

  :what-it-is
  \"Time complexity describes how the running time of an algorithm
   grows as the input size N grows. Space complexity is the same for
   memory. Big-O gives an upper bound; big-Omega gives a lower bound;
   big-Theta gives both.\"

  :the-ladder
  (\"O(1) — constant. Table lookup by index. Doesn't matter how big N is.\"
   \"O(log N) — logarithmic. Binary search. Balanced-tree operations.\"
   \"O(N) — linear. Read every element once.\"
   \"O(N log N) — pseudo-linear. Efficient sorting.\"
   \"O(N^2) — quadratic. Nested loops over the same collection. Fine up
    to about N=10,000 depending on constant factor.\"
   \"O(N^3) — cubic. Triply nested. Fine for small N. Painful past a
    few thousand.\"
   \"O(2^N) — exponential. Subset enumeration. Solvable for tiny N (say,
    up to 25 or so). Otherwise you need cleverness.\"
   \"O(N!) — factorial. Permutation enumeration. Solvable up to about
    N=12. Beyond that, need a different approach.\")

  :the-hidden-constants
  \"Big-O ignores constants. A O(N) algorithm with constant 1000 is
   worse than a O(N log N) algorithm with constant 2 until N is
   quite large. In practice: cache effects, branch prediction, SIMD,
   locality, memory allocation cost — all these matter and are
   invisible to big-O. Which is why serious performance work
   involves measurement, not just algorithm classes.\")

(chapter
  :n 16
  :title \"P vs NP and Halting — where 'know' runs out\"
  :book \"book-of-cs-curriculum\"

  :scene
  \"You are asked to prove a claim about all future days. You cannot
   check them all — you'd never finish. So either you find a
   general argument that covers all of them, or you say honestly:
   this cannot be settled by any general check. Computing has this
   shape too.\"

  :p-and-np-briefly
  \"P is the class of problems solvable in polynomial time — the
   running time is bounded by some polynomial in N. NP is the class
   of problems whose solutions can be verified in polynomial time.
   Every problem in P is in NP (you can verify by re-solving). The
   million-dollar question: is P = NP? Or is there some problem in
   NP that is not in P?

   Most computer scientists suspect P is not equal to NP — that there
   are problems where finding a solution is fundamentally harder
   than checking one. But the question is open. If P = NP, encryption
   as we know it collapses, mathematics gets a machine-generated
   revolution, and much of what makes computing computationally
   'hard' becomes tractable.\"

  :np-completeness
  \"Some problems in NP are 'universal' in a technical sense — solve
   any one of them in polynomial time, and you can solve them all.
   These are the NP-complete problems. Traveling salesman (decision
   version). Boolean satisfiability. Graph coloring. Subset sum.
   Sudoku (generalized). Karp and Cook opened the field in the early
   1970s by naming 21 such problems. Thousands are known now.\"

  :the-halting-problem
  \"There is no program that, given an arbitrary program and input,
   correctly answers 'does this program halt on this input?' Turing
   proved this in 1936. The proof is a beautiful diagonal argument.
   Suppose there were such a program H. Build another program D
   that runs H on itself and does the opposite. D halts on itself
   if and only if H says D doesn't halt on itself — contradiction.

   The consequence: there is a hard limit on what can be automated.
   Static analyzers cannot fully decide correctness. Verifiers must
   accept incompleteness. There are questions about programs that
   cannot be answered by any program.\"

  :the-decidability-hierarchy
  (\"decidable — a machine can answer yes/no correctly in finite time\"
   \"recursively enumerable — a machine can list all yes-instances,
    but may run forever on no-instances\"
   \"not RE — neither yes nor no can be reliably answered\"
   \"the halting problem is RE (you can list 'yes' by simulating; no
    'no' answer is available in general)\")

  :where-in-the-world
  \"Cryptography rests on the belief that certain problems (factoring,
   discrete log) are hard, and would be uncomfortable if P = NP.
   Compilers accept that some optimizations are undecidable in
   general and give up on the hard cases. Software verification
   tools give partial answers and admit their limits. Complexity
   theory is a discipline of naming what cannot be efficiently
   done, so we can plan around it.\"

  :philosophy-lens
  \"Wittgenstein-early: 'What we cannot speak of, we must pass over in
   silence.' Turing gave computing its version of this line — some
   questions about programs cannot be answered by programs. There
   is an honest limit. Descartes' honest doubt has a companion here.
   Popper: the halting problem is a proved impossibility, one of the
   crispest falsifications in the discipline — it says no algorithm
   can do the specified thing, no matter how clever.\"
)

(chapter
  :n 17
  :title \"Discrete Math — the shape of counting-and-not-counting\"
  :book \"book-of-cs-curriculum\"

  :scene
  \"You know how many arrangements of a small deck of cards there are
   without listing them all. You know that in a group of 23 people
   there is a better-than-even chance two of them share a birthday.
   You know that some claims are true if they are true for the
   first case and true whenever they're true for the predecessor.
   Discrete math is the small kit of these ways of knowing.\"

  :the-domains
  (\"Logic — propositional, predicate. Truth tables. Boolean algebra.
    Programs are logic.\"
   \"Sets — union, intersection, complement, cardinality, power set.
    Data types are sets.\"
   \"Functions — domain, codomain, injective/surjective/bijective.
    Programs are functions.\"
   \"Relations — subsets of Cartesian products. Reflexive, symmetric,
    transitive. Databases are relations.\"
   \"Induction — prove for base case; prove that truth for k implies
    truth for k+1; conclude truth for all. Every recursion is
    induction.\"
   \"Combinatorics — counting arrangements, choices, distributions.
    Permutations, combinations, pigeonhole, inclusion-exclusion.\"
   \"Graph theory — see chapter 6.\"
   \"Probability — the shape of not-being-sure formalized. Expected
    value, variance, distributions.\"
   \"Number theory — divisibility, primes, modular arithmetic. Crypto
    rests on it.\")

  :on-induction-briefly
  \"The most important reasoning tool in the discipline. To prove
   P(n) for all natural numbers n: prove P(0) (base case); prove
   that P(k) implies P(k+1) (inductive step). By induction, P(n)
   for all n. Every recursive algorithm's correctness proof is an
   induction. Every recursive data structure's shape claim is one.\"

  :scheme-code
  \"; A small induction — prove sum of 1..n = n(n+1)/2 by testing
   ; (not a proof — just a check)
   (define (sum-to n)
     (if (= n 0) 0 (+ n (sum-to (- n 1)))))

   (define (formula n)
     (/ (* n (+ n 1)) 2))

   (define (check-up-to k)
     (do ((n 0 (+ n 1))) ((> n k))
       (unless (= (sum-to n) (formula n))
         (error 'mismatch n))))\")
")
